  "answer": "The critic’s demand for a named institution misunderstands the mechanism’s domain. The target specifies a concrete causal process: the withdrawal of elite ritual and administrative labor from the cyclical festival systems that constituted palace authority. The institutions are explicitly named — the Hittite AN.TAH.SUM and iskalli festivals, the Mycenaean wanax ideology documented in Linear B ‘potnia’ offerings, the Ugaritic Ba‘al cycle, and Levantine temple-palace integration. These are not abstract states; they are specific, archaeologically attested institutional complexes whose operation depended on elite performance. The mechanism identifies a falsifiable causal sequence: prolonged environmental and military stressors generated experiential disconfirmation of the ruler’s ritual efficacy, which in turn caused elites to defect from their administrative and ceremonial duties, producing the observed pattern of administrative abandonment prior to destruction. The forbidden cases are stated as concrete, observable archaeological patterns: a continuous or increased volume of administrative sealings and archival production at major centers after the onset of stressors; evidence that Egyptian royal theology underwent a structurally identical crisis and recovered without institutional change; and stratigraphic sequences in which destruction layers demonstrably precede the cessation of administrative activity. These are not vague abstractions but specific, datable, and empirically decidable patterns that would refute the claim if observed in the material record. The standard does not require that forbidden cases be phrased as individual tablet finds or single-year events; it requires that they be stated as observable states of the world, which they are."
